ce:section.ce:para:
The DPV method was utilized to measure the concentration of 5-FU at the suggested modified electrode: SNW-1/Cu-MOFs/GQDs/GCE, due to its higher sensitivity and efficiency. In order to examine the electroanalytical abilities of the SNW-1/Cu-MOFs/GQDs/GCE, we recorded its DPV profiles at various concentrations of 5-FU in 0.1 M PBS solution under the optimal measuring conditions (pH=7.0, the amount of SNW-1/Cu-MOFs/GQDs on the GCE: 2 mg/mL and potential interval: 1.05 to 1.3 V). It was evident that as the 5-FU concentration increases (Fig. 4
                        ), the peak current also increased in a proportional manner. The calibration curve, illustrating the correlation between changes in the anodic peak current of the plotted DPV grams and the concentration of 5-FU within the range of 0.01–32 and 32–65 μM, in inset of Fig. 4. The mathematical expressions for the two linear relationships are obtained as Ip(µA) = 0.974 C5-FU+0.9152 (R2 = 0.9903) and Ip(µA) = 0.6532 C5-FU+0.12.052 (R2 = 0.9911). According to the calculations and experiments conducted for confirmation, the estimated detection limit (LOD= (3 × SD)/slope) and quantitation limit (LOQ= (10 × SD)/slope) [73] are 35 nM and 119 nM respectively, indicating that the present sensor is capable of identifying extremely low levels of the 5-FU. The obtained results (as clearly shown in Table 1
                        ) reveal that the proposed sensor: SNW-1/Cu-MOFs/GQDs/GCE, has a higher sensitivity and wider linear range for detecting of 5-FU compared to other modified electrodes in the literature. In the other words, as shown in Table 1, the new constructed sensor; SNW-1/Cu-MOFs/GQDs/GCE, demonstrates comparable/superior performance compared to the other previously reported modified electrodes.
